    <item>
      <title>Re: sShaman Prayers Have Been Heard By the Developers!</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&amp;message.id=13677#M13677</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;I felt like responding on one more thing, I would do this on the site but I cannot.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I can understand that some of the folks from the Crucible think they are representing the majority of Shamans, and that somehow, the majority is always right.&amp;nbsp; Unfortunately, some posters there have also shown great immaturity when it comes to dealing with those who disagree, myself included.&amp;nbsp; I think that these kind of attitudes have.. well, kept opposition from posting on their site.&amp;nbsp; I've looked at some of the messages there and think one of the most productive things the folks on the Crucible could do is promote a more open minded discussion on these issues.&amp;nbsp; I respect many of the folks there, but when they turn into children because they don't get their way, it sure doesn't make anyone want to help them.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;One person, on a post about this thread, was talking about how they were in such a rage they couldn't possibly respond constructively...&amp;nbsp; What in hell do&amp;nbsp;they have to be enraged about?&amp;nbsp; It is a game, and I think&amp;nbsp;every *faction* of the shaman dispute might need to come together, both educated naysayers (moreso than myself)&amp;nbsp;and pro-upgrade, to work on something.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;In the last shaman thread, I went and presented my own arguments, from my point of view.&amp;nbsp; When corrected, I acknowledged that, but when I wouldn't back down... the "children" began flinging insults (not just at myself) and lost their ability to logically reason why I was wrong.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Many stayed above it and kudos to them.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I'm going to tell you though, unless you can get the reins on the community (listen to Litgruv, he's got the right ideas on how to encourage change) and can make a steady argument for why things need to change, you're not likely to get much attention from anyone but other posters.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Here is what honestly needs to change:&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;1. Stop talking about Beastlords, or any other class... Focus on our class.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;2. Don't turn into toddlers when people disagree... convince them otherwise or just walk away.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;3. Don't use arguments that&amp;nbsp;you can tell the Dev team doesn't care about.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;"We haven't had many upgrades since Kunark." "Yeah, so?"&amp;nbsp; Prove you need the upgrades!&amp;nbsp; &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;"We haven't had a new, good slow, since 51." "Well, you can tell we think slow is overpowering considering we made so many mitigating mobs... next?"&amp;nbsp;Look to new solutions there, slow isn't likely to get better or more powerful. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;"We want to do more damage!"&amp;nbsp; "Exactly how much more damage do you think you need?"&amp;nbsp; Define it, prove that is what is holding us back, without comparing to others but not stepping on their toes.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;"We need better heals!" "Nah, we've got other healing classes, we think you're where you belong."&amp;nbsp; Prove them wrong.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;4. Don't complain, don't attack,&amp;nbsp;and put a leash&amp;nbsp;on those who do.&amp;nbsp; You'll show stronger ability to reason and think and you'll do better at proving your points.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I remember the letter that was put together by the Shaman community... and, I do have to say it was not that convincing, because it lacked the arguments and the support that went into making the document.&amp;nbsp; A whole page full of notes and thoughts would be condensed into one little line, and it was too broad reaching for the folks up there to grasp it.&amp;nbsp; It was a good effort, but someone needed to stand up and say "This is the unanimous direction that the Shaman community wants to go in, and this is how we shall try to accomplish it."&amp;nbsp; The document before was more of "We know we need something, this is what we think we need, you guys figure out what is best" and that wasn't likely to work.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;So go back to the Crucible, find some direction, let some people come in and tell you where you're making mistakes or that they think it is bad ideas and find a logical way to counter every argument they bring.&amp;nbsp; It was not me or the few who disagreed on TNZ who prevented a single thing from happening, it is a remainingly divided Shaman community that could not become focused on a single direction.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Honestly?&amp;nbsp; The shaman class, as listed in its own description, is supposed to be the ultimate support class.&amp;nbsp; The situation as the game has progressed has nullified that in some situations... buffs are useless, slow is mitigated, and so on... so, considering that and the fact that in mine and others opinions that a 65, non raiding shaman, regular LDoN/BoT etc, remains a balanced and desired&amp;nbsp;entity, find some solutions for the consideration for those who are at a disadvantage.&amp;nbsp; And find some focus, take that original letter and vote on one of the topics in that... and let that mark the new direction for the class.&amp;nbsp; More dps, better heals, better buffs... whatever, and then enforce it and prove the need and application of it.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I just want to note, I am not saying the original letter was bad... it wasn't and I commend the efforts of those who made it, but it did turn out to be unconvincing for those who do not read every other post on the Crucible.&amp;nbsp; There was lots of thoughts and theories and expectations and hopes for change, but not really that much evidence or real solutions and speculation on application of those solutions.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Good luck.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;And yes, I am still playing my shaman =)&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
